{{Infobox cricket ground | ground_name = Parr and Wisden's Ground | nickname = | country = England | image = | location = [[Leamington Spa]], [[Warwickshire]] | establishment = 1848 <small>(first recorded match)</small> | seating_capacity = | end1 = | end2 = | year1 = 1849-1850 | club1 = [[North of England cricket team|North]] | date = 28 August | year = 2010 | source = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/567.html Ground profile }}
'''Parr and Wisden's Ground''' was a [[cricket]] ground in [[Leamington Spa]], [[Warwickshire]]. The ground was named after the famous duo of [[George Parr (cricketer)|George Parr]] and [[John Wisden]], who were the proprietors of the ground.<ref>[http://www.leamingtoncricket.co.uk/history/default.aspx A Club be Formed, A Brief History by Mark L Ryan]</ref>
The first recorded match on the ground was in 1848, when Leamington played an [[All-England Eleven]].<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/567_misc.html Other matches played on Parr and Wisden's Ground]</ref> The ground hosted 2 [[first-class cricket|first-class]] matches, the first of which came in 1849 and was between the [[North of England cricket team|North]] and the [[South of England cricket team|South]]. The second and final first-class match held at the ground came the following year in a repeat of the previous years fixture,<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/567_f.html First-Class Matches played on Parr and Wisden's Ground]</ref> with Parr and Wisden themselves playing in the North team. The final recorded match held on the ground came in 1862 and saw the [[Free Foresters Cricket Club|Free Foresters]] play an All-England Eleven.
As well as being a venue for cricket, the ground was also a notable [[archery]] venue.<ref>[http://www.rlsas.com/comps/hosted/lmc/lmc-1851.php Royal Leamington Spa Archery Society]</ref> Today the ground has mostly been built on, though part of it makes up [[Victoria Park, Leamington Spa|Victoria Park]].
